The best approach for file system statics is **`System.IO.Abstractions`** — a battle-tested NuGet package that wraps `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, etc. behind `IFileSystem`. No need to write custom wrappers.

**1. Install the package:**
```
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

**2. Register in DI (`Program.cs` / `Startup.cs`):**
```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

**3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes:**
```csharp
public class ConfigService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDirectory(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

**4. Test with `MockFileSystem`:**
```
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```
```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});

var service = new ConfigService(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", service.Load("/config.json"));

service.Save("/out.json", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/out.json"));

Assert.False(mockFs.Directory.Exists("/nope"));
```

**Key points:**
- Only wrap methods you actually call — `IFileSystem` covers all three of yours (`File.ReadAllText`, `File.WriteAllText`, `Directory.Exists`).
- Register as `AddSingleton` — the default `FileSystem` implementation is stateless.
- Once injected, use `migrate-static-to-wrapper` (ask me!) to bulk-replace call sites across your project.
